^B@2^*BMB: ^*N|cp||at|There is a way to know which side-suit king opener holds. The most efficient way to respond to 5NT is to control-bid your cheapest king. Thus, if opener has the club king, he bids 6@C, and you can bid a confident 7@S. If instead, partner has a red-suit king (or two), once he doesn't bid 6@C, you know that he doesn't have the @CK.|
PG| ***** 69 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMB: ^*N|cp||at|That way, you can be sure that a grand slam could not be a good contract. Responding to 5NT by control-bidding your lowest king is sometimes referred to as the "improved king-ask." It can be the key to knowing whether you should bid a grand slam. Be aware, however, that the improved king-ask can get you too high when a suit other than spades is trumps. Therefore, many RKC players revert to just showing number of kings when spades is not trumps.|
