AT|

Responses of 5@C and 5@D when playing 1430:
* 5@C shows 1 or 4 key cards.
* 5@D shows 0 or 3 key cards.
These bids neither promise nor deny the trump queen (or extra length).|
PG| ***** 72 ***** |


AT|

Responses of 5@H and 5@S
Both show 2 or 5 key cards.
5@H denies the trump queen (or extra length in the trump suit).
5@S shows the trump queen (or extra length in the trump suit).|
PG| ***** 73 ***** |


AT|

Asking for the trump queen:
After a response of 5@C or 5@D, a bid in the cheapest new suit asks partner if he has the trump queen (or extra length in trump). If partner has the queen (or extra length), he control-bids his cheapest king. |
PG| ***** 74 ***** |


AT|

Alternate ways of showing kings after 5NT:
Traditional number of side-suit kings.
Control-bidding cheapest king but only when spades are trumps. Some pairs have additional agreements here to learn about other kings as well. Control-bidding cheapest king regardless of which suit is trumps. If your cheapest king is in a suit that is higher-ranking than the trump suit, use your judgment on whether to show it.|
